        $postDescriptionsEng = [
            'Titinu: "Oh hello! I hadn’t noticed you! Are you looking around out of curiosity or are you wondering what kind of unusual place this is? Actually, even I was a bit surprised the first time I came here. It was the first time I noticed this short staircase leading to a quiet garden. It seemed to me like an interesting place, so I slipped inside right away. It immediately struck me as a magical place, a bit mysterious and hidden from all passers-by, by car or on foot, along the road running beside it. Once inside the garden, I looked around: I was right, this place is unlike any other! The trees, with their dark leaves, protected me from the sun and all around ran small channels of water, but that was not what surprised me the most. As I turned to the right and the left, I saw silent figures: entirely white or black statues, and others whose forms I could not distinguish. By then, my curiosity was piqued: what kind of place had I wandered into? What did these statues represent? Some of them remind me of people, but I wasn’t entirely sure. I absolutely had to find out! So, I walked to the door, went inside and went down the stairs. Those two rooms contained everything: paintings with thousands of details and tiny flags, some so small I could hardly see them, strange sculptures with horns and planet earth entirely covered with minute bronze figures! Even the materials were somewhat unusual and they did not look to me like the materials we normally use in art class: there was iron, textiles and even concrete sculptures: like those used in walls or pavements. It took me a while to order my thoughts; I had to ask quite a few people and I came back more than once. By now, was almost an expert! I realised that all these works, all these strange objects, had a profound but simple meaning, that anyone could understand. As if that were not enough, there were some special hands behind it: the hands of an courageous man who led an adventurous life. To find out more, we must down the stairs.. Oh, wait, I haven’t told you anything about myself yet: Orani is my home and I live close by, at the end of the street. My family and friends all call me Titinu, and you can also call me that. Once we go in, I will introduce you to a special person."',
            'Titinu: "Here I am again! Are you wondering what these figures are? How are they meant to be viewed and from what strange material are they made? I understand… even I had the same questions at the beginning. For now, all I can tell you is that they were created by the person with the special hands, I already told you about, whose name was Costantino Nivola. But to understand something more about him, the person we have to speak to is Ruth: she knows everything." Ruth: "Oh, there you are, Titinu, and I see several new faces behind you! How wonderful to be here with you and to be able to tell you about the adventures I have experienced and about Costantino, Antine as I used to call him, who was with me the whole time. My name is Ruth Guggenheim. What? What did you say? It seems to be an unusual surname? Well, you are right! My family was of Jewish origin and I was born in Germany in a year which now seems very long ago: 1917. Those were very difficult years: even though I was only a child, I well remember how worried my father was because in Germany crimes and violence against Jews were increasing. So, we fled to Italy, without knowing that that troubles would catch up with us even there … but I’ll tell you more about that later on. By this time, I was no longer a child but girl of 16. Even after changing country and city, my passions remained intact: I was interested in art and loved to create. So, I enrolled in the Art Institute and it was there that I met Antine. I must say, it wasn’t hard to notice him: in the entire school, which was in Monza, there were only three lads from Sardinia, each more talented than the last. Antine and I were drawn to each other immediately, and we were never parted after that, even though we came from very different worlds, he from a tiny village in Sardinia and I from a large German city. Every work in this museum reminds me of a different time in our life together. Here, for example, Antine had just landed an important job. Try to imagine being on Fifth Avenue in New York, one of the most famous streets in the world. Cars, yellow taxis, people walking fast, towering skyscrapers. In the middle of all this, in the fifties, there was a special shop owned by Olivetti, who sold typewriters and calculators, but who also a new idea about beauty and work. Adriano Olivetti, the director, believed that when people entered the workplace, they deserved to find harmony, light and beauty. This is the reason he called in modern architects and artists, among whom was Antine himself. The sketches which you see here are his first thoughts for decorating the walls and façades of the shop. It was a revolutionary idea: one didn’t have to go to a museum to see art but it was there, mixed in with everyday items. But let’s move on – I want to show you another work …"',
            'Ruth: "Now I’m going to take you to a very different place from the streets of New York and shops full of people. A small room so rich in colours and filled with objects that it’s difficult to make them all out. I am very attached to this painting because on the right you can see me, Ruth and a little higher up, almost as though suspended in mid-air, is Pietro, our first child. As you can see, I am no longer a young girl but a woman. If you look a bit closer you will see I am wearing a concentrated and rather serious expression. No wonder! By this stage Antine and I had already faced thousands of difficulties! A few years after we met, racial laws were introduced even in Italy and life for Jews became even more difficult. For this reason, and so we could stay together, Antine and I decided to escape together to America. It seemed like a real adventure, but in actual fact it was very difficult: Antine did not speak English well and he struggled to find work. I, on the other hand, knew English a bit better and started working in a factory and then as a nanny. Little by little things improved: Antine found a job that he enjoyed very much, as a graphic designer for American magazines and got to know some of the great artists and architects of the time, including Corbusier, who became a great friend. The painting you see before you dates back to this period: our home was his refuge. In this picture you can see me preparing a meal, surrounded by plates, fruit and bottles. It may seem like an everyday scene, such as you would see in your own home on any day. However, for Antine, this was a very important subject: everyday life, care for others. If you look at the painting more closely, you will see many details: our dinner, the lamp which hung from the ceiling but also the brushes and the palette that Antine used every day. The colours also remind me of a warm blanket and make me feel at home. Titinu will tell you about the next work, since by now he knows it very well and it is one of his favourites."',
            'Titinu: "I would like to speak to you about this figure, because the first time I saw it, I thought it was something of a mystery to be uncovered. It is as if Nivola himself was trying to tell me something that I missed initially. The colour reminds me of a nail which has been left outside for a long time and is rusting. At first, I found the figure a bit intimidating, but then I noticed that it curved towards me, as though embracing everything which stood before it. I looked at the label beside it, sure that it would be able to help me: in small script was written: female figure from the series “The Ancestors”. I knew that the ancestors were like our great-great grandmothers, people who lived a long time before us. So, in Nivola’s imagination, this figure was like a grandmother from a time long, long ago. The most curious feature though that that in creating it, Nivola did not use stone, or carve rock, working in materials that had certainly existed since ancient times. No, he used iron, sheet metal as Ruth explained to me later, which was a very common material in New York and in Italy and used for building skyscrapers and ultra-modern buildings. Two different worlds are thus united in this figure, the great-great grandmothers, a long-ago time and a modern material which contemporaries of Nivola would have used every day. Perhaps it was his way of saying that even in our fast-paced, technological lives we remain linked by a slender thread to all those who came before us who dreamed, longed and asked questions just as we do. But this is just my opinion and it’s possible that I am wrong! I would be very interested to know what you think, what does the figure remind you of and how does it make you feel."',
            'Ruth: "There you are again! I was waiting for you. We are now in front of… what did you say? You, there at the back with the fringe, what does this work remind you of… a wall? A rather unusual wall with shapes, little hollows, figures? I don’t mind at all and I am sure that even Antine would have a good laugh, because you are quite right. This work is created in concrete, the same material as house walls and pavement kerbs. Antine knew it well because when he was still young, he started work as a labourer and later a mason, like his father. You should know that Orani was famous for its masons of which he was one. He later chose another path, and fell in love with art, but he never forgot what he had learned in Orani. He thus found a way of combining the work of a mason with that of an artist. Would you like to know another secret? Antine discovered the technique that he used for this work through play! Yes, you heard right, he was playing in the sand at the seaside with our two children, as one does in the summer, and this gave him the idea of using it as a mould. He would create a design in the sand and then, little by little, pour cement over it. Once the cement had dried, he would lift it away and the figures that you see would be imprinted upon it. Architects loved these works! Because they were works of art, but hard-wearing, made of the same material as the buildings being constructed and could be safely moved. This was hugely successful and Antine created many for a great number of buildings in America. It was also his way of saying that art could be anywhere: on government buildings, offices, in the heart of the cities. According to him, art and beauty should be accessible to everyone and can improve society. It was a grand dream and Antine never stopped nurturing it."',
            'Titinu: "Another work, another material: this time in textile, like a patterned rug. Like me, you must be wondering: but how many things did Nivola know how to do? Cement, stone, sand, metal and now also textiles. Perhaps I should tell you that here he had a little help. As Ruth said of Nivola, he very much liked the idea of art becoming part of everyday life, in offices and homes. He was also a sculptor, and not everyone has space for sculptures at home, besides the fact that they are very heavy and can break. So, he spoke about this with a dear architect friend named Corbusier, who came up with a brilliant suggestion: why not make your sculptures light and supple? This was a terrific idea for the modern world where people move house often and spaces are small. Nivola took him at his word and made various designs of his sculptures and sent them to a little town in Sardinia called Sarule, famous for its weavers. His idea was to turn the stone sculpture into woven tapestries, which are like large carpets which hang on walls. What you see in front of you is one of these tapestries. Here Nivola depicts a Sardinian shepherd, strong and sturdy, as he leads his flocks across meadows and mountains. Even though he was living in the United States at that time, he never forgot the hills around Orani, the sound of the sheep bells and the dry-stone walls. Designing this figure was a way of saying: “I do not forget where I come from.” When the tapestry was complete, the weavers of Sarule who had made it, said that it was truly beautiful, which Nivola took as a great compliment."',
            'Titinu: "It’s me again! This work concerns Orani and since I live here, I simply have to tell you about it. These drawings with leaves, walls, people and animals represented the great dream of Costantino Nivola: it is called “Pergola Village” which translates, more or less, as pergola-covered village. Pergolas are structures in wood or iron over which various plants climb, vines, roses or wisteria, where leaves provide shade in the summer while allowing light to shine through in winter when the leaves fall. Here, Nivola imagines all the houses in Oriani would be linked by pergolas so that walking through the village would be like walking through a garden, cool and surrounded by leaves and flowers. It is a wonderful idea that goes beyond sculpture, beyond painting, and beyond anything he had done up to that moment. This project would enable people to chat outside their homes without getting burned by the sun or getting to drenched when it rains. Nivola may have left this little village to travel to New York, but he never forgot Orani. On the contrary, the further away he was, the more he thought about it. He said he felt like a link detached from its chain. In designing this project, he wanted to gift his village a kind of embrace made from houses, colours and plants, strengthening the sense of community and belonging between the inhabitants. If you look at the other panels you will see many other features of Orani that Antine remembered clearly from his childhood: women making bread and placing it in the oven, donkeys carrying wood. The project you see here was published in an important American magazine: there, people who had never heard of Orani began to study these small Sardinian houses, all covered with greenery."',
            'Ruth: "Something curious happens in this gallery: Antine does not portray people, but… his own sculptures. It is as if he has taken the three-dimensional works that he had already created – that he had made from cement, stone or other materials – and decided to look at them in a new way, this time with a painter’s eye. The paintings which you see here are part of the series which he called “Portraits of sculptures”. Many things change when a sculpture is turned into a painting: depth becomes surface, shadow becomes colour, volume is restated in lines. Nivola used this transformation to understand his own shapes better: his gaze cut through them, simplified them, exaggerated them, at times rendered them unrecognisable. It was a continual dialogue between his work as a sculptor and that as a painter. As you look at these three paintings, try to imagine which parts correspond to curves, recesses and indentations in the original sculptures. But it is not important to make an exact guess: what is important is to understand the way in which colour substitutes for materials. The shades are often intense and unrealistic, because they are not intended to replicate the surface of the sculpture; they seek to portray their internal energy, its character. In a certain sense, these paintings are also an act of remembrance: Antine looks back at his own body of work, retraces it, distils it, recreates it on canvas. It is as if he were writing a description of a person he knew intimately – himself – but, instead of words, he used the forms of his own works."',
            'Ruth: "Orani was Antine’s first home, where his family lived and his childhood memories were formed, but the United States were also extremely important for us. We lived there for almost all our adult lives, raised our children, experimented and created. We were no different from the many persons who set out in pursuit of the “American dream”, opportunity and prosperity. As you have seen, Antine tried his hand at many things: painting, sculpture, architecture. In this instance, he imagined a huge monument which represented the American symbol for excellence: its flag. His plan was to create a gigantic American flag: the waves which you see would become walls and the stars would become soaring columns. Bring your eyes closer. The stripes are not smooth: they resemble the waves of the sea or dunes sculpted by the wind. The stars, however, are not flat, but have become tiny three-dimensional forms on top of so many slim columns, so that they seem to be leaping towards the sky. It is a trick that Nivola often used: taking something flat and making it explode into space, something that cannot only be viewed from one side only because one must move around it. People would have been able to walk through them as freely as they would have been able to pursue their dreams in this land of opportunity. The most impressive element would certainly have been the fifty columns that formed the stars which represented the fifty American states. Antine did not look at the United States with his eyes closed: he was aware of its injustices and its faults. At the same time New York, Long Island had become our second home and he wished to memorialise it with this monument."',
            'Ruth: "Pause for a moment in front of this painting. To start with, it seems like an enormous black tangle: lines, curls, interlocking squares. But if you narrow your eyes a bit, something happens: those scribbles become houses, windows, streets, cars, tiny figures trapped in traffic. It is a city bursting with movement, noise, confusion. It is New York seen through the eyes of Antine. When we arrived there, fleeing from Europe because of its racial laws, everything seemed incredible: the soaring skyscrapers, lights, bridges, people from all parts of the world walking side by side. Antine was fascinated: from the moment he arrived he painted New York continually, as if by drawing it, he could come to understand it better. This painting, however, came from much later, and by then Antine had seen the other side: the unrelenting traffic, people rushing past each other without a glance, the injustices and the poverty hidden behind the glittering shopfronts. He does not pretend that everything is perfect in this painting: he shows you an extremely beautiful city … but also exhausting, complicated and at times ruthless. It is a city of grand buildings and people from all over the world: can you recognise all the flags that Antine painted? His “incredible city” is something of a warning: it tells us that cities are wonderful, but we need to pause from time to time, so as not to get lost in the confusion. As you look at this painting perhaps you will discover something you never thought of before: even chaos can be drawn, observed, understood. And, above all, we must ask ourselves what type of city do we wish to create when we grow up."',
            'Titinu: "My grandmother told me a strange thing: that the older you become, truly aged, the more you think back to when you were young and those long-ago memories take on an almost magical quality. I think something similar also happened to Nivola and the older he became the more he delved back into his earliest memories where he always found inspiration. This large all-white statue, with a slight curve at its centre, he titled “Mother” and then we immediately understand what it is: a mother holding within her womb the secret of a wonderful child. In creating this, he thought back to his home when he was little and to the “rounded wall” where bread was baked. At the time bread was extremely precious. The curve in the wall, where the bread was baked, thus concealed a treasure, the promise of satisfying hunger once and for all, as a mother hides in her womb the secret of a wonderful child. Thus, Nivola blends his earliest memories, with a simple but extremely powerful figure. This mother seems to open her arms in an embrace towards all those who stand before her. Nivola chose marble for this sculpture, a noble and extremely hard stone. Perhaps he chose it for this very reason: to tell us a parent’s love is not easily broken."',
            'Ruth: "At first glance, this large, dark sphere seems to be a mysterious planet lost in space. If you focus your eyes more closely: it is not smooth like a ball, the surface is covered with small forms, curves, crisscrossing grooves, ridges. It is as if someone has modelled a great many tiny figures, side by side, so that not even a single millimetre of space remains free. This is the reason the work is titled “The overpopulated earth”: an earth on which there are so many beings that they cannot be counted one by one. Nivola frequently worked with hard materials such as cement or marble, but here he returned to a form of modelling much closer to play: kneading, adding, pressing, cutting. Imagine his hands moving around the sphere, continually adding tiny features, as though he was writing a story without words. Every feature would be a person, an animal, a house, an idea. None is large, none dominates over the others: together they form the skin of the planet. He seems to ask though a sculpture such as this: “What will become of the Earth when there are more and more of us? Let’s try and play a game: choose any point on the surface with your eyes and focus on it for a moment. What do you seem to see? A face, a body, an animal or just a blob? Now shift your gaze, move a bit around the sphere and look for another detail. You will realise that the work never ends: the more you look, the more new forms you discover. And perhaps you would like to think about this also: if the earth could speak, what would it say to us all living huddled together on its surface?"'
        ];

